<h2>USA FEDERAL NEWS</h2>
<strong>CPSC Withdraws Heavy Metals Testing Exemption For Unfinished and Untreated Trunk Wood</strong>

The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) had published a Direct Final Rule determining that unfinished and untreated trunk wood does not contain heavy elements that would exceed the limits specified in the toy safety standard ASTM F963-11.  This final rule, which was anticipated to become effective September 15, 2015, would exempt unfinished and untreated trunk wood from the required third party testing for the heavy elements listed in ASTM F963-11. However, the CPSC received significant adverse comments causing them to withdraw the Final Rule on September 10, 2015 without instituting a second comment period on the action.

The CPSC will address the adverse comments they received in a separate Federal Register Notice yet to be published.

<strong>CPSC Solicits Comments on Petition to Declare Organohalogen Flame Retardants "Banned Hazardous Substances"</strong>

The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) published a Notice of Petition for Rulemaking on August 19, 2015 to solicit comments regarding a petition to declare several categories of products containing additive organohalogen flame retardants to be “banned hazardous substances” under the Federal Hazardous Substances Act (FHSA). The petition, filed by Earthjustice and the Consumer Federation of America jointly with other organizations, claims that these flame retardants are used extensively in certain consumer product categories and will migrate out of the products to the indoor environment.   They further assert that due to their inherent toxicity, exposure to the chemicals will result in adverse human health impacts such as reproductive, neurologic, endocrine, and immunologic disorders as well as cancer.

The petition requests a ban on using organohalogen flame retardants in upholstered furniture, children’s products, childcare articles and toys, mattresses and electronic devices with added organohalogen flame retardants in their plastic casing.  Comments on the Petition for Rulemaking will be accepted by the Commission through October 19, 2015. See the <a href="https://www.federalregister.gov/a/2015-20454" target="_blank">Federal Register Notice</a> for further information. 

<strong>CPSC and CBP Announce Voluntary Testing of "Single Window" Electronic Filing of Trade Data</strong>

The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) in conjunction with U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) intends to conduct a test to assess the electronic filing of certain trade data for regulated finished consumer products under CPSC jurisdiction.  The CPSC is requesting participants to test this “single window” designed to facilitate electronic collection, processing, sharing, and reviewing of trade data and documents required by federal agencies during the cargo import and export processes. The initial intent of this pilot was to require electronic filing of Certificates of Compliance for all regulated imported products.  However, after consultation with stakeholders, the Commission has, for the time being, limited the test to collection of certain minimal targeting/enforcement data, hoping to facilitate the flow of legitimate trade and to enhance targeting of noncompliant products.
Interested parties may file for voluntary participation by October 5, 2015.  To read more, <a href="https://federalregister.gov/a/2015-20707" target="_blank">click here</a>.

<strong>ASTM Publishes Updates to Consumer Trampoline Standard</strong>

ASTM has published ASTM F381-15 Standard Safety Specification for Components, Assembly, Use, and Labeling of Consumer Trampolines.  This updated specification is intended:
<ol>
	<li>To reduce the demonstrated hazards associated with the use of trampolines by consumers;</li>
	<li>To address trampolines used in a home environment by a single user; and </li>
	<li>To not apply to institutional trampolines or trampolines intended for use on water.</li>
</ol>
Trampolines that adhere to this specification are not recommended for use by children under six years of age.

