<h2>USA STATE NEWS</h2>

<strong>Updates to <a href="http://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/38/title38ch16-Dsec0.html" target="_blank">Maine's Toxic Chemicals in Children's Products Law</a></strong>

Maine’s Department of Environmental Protection (DEP) has published its triennial update to its Chemicals of High Concern (CHC) list on July 21, 2015, removing those chemicals that were elevated to Priority Chemicals and those not meeting criteria for a CHC.  There are currently 36 <a href="http://www.maine.gov/dep/safechem/highconcern/index.html" target="_blank">chemicals on the list</a>.

Additionally, Maine’s DEP has designated Formaldehyde as a Priority Chemical requiring reporting in certain children’s products.  This rule became effective July 26, 2015 with reporting required 180 days after this day.  <a href="http://www.ansecogroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/096c885-1.pdf" target="_blank">Read More</a>

