<strong>New European Standard for Nickel Release</strong>

In July 2015, the European Committee for Standardisation (CEN) approved Amendment 1 to the standard for nickel release, which is now to become EN 1811:2011+A1:2015 "Reference test method for release of nickel from all post assemblies which are inserted into pierced parts of the human body and articles intended to come into direct and prolonged contact with the skin".

This new standard simplifies the requirement for compliance by removing the “inconclusive” test result range.  Under the new standard, results that fall within that range are now considered “compliant”.  Additionally, due to the 46% measurement uncertainty of the method, the test articles are defined as non-compliant only when the quantified result is greater than or equal to 0.88 µg/cm<sup>2</sup>/week for non-body piercing articles and to 0.35 µg/cm<sup>2</sup>/week for body piercing articles. According to the European Standard EN 1811:2011+A1:2015, conflicting standards shall be withdrawn by January 2016 at the latest.

