<strong>Updated European Standard for Bunk Beds and High Beds - EN 747</strong>

In June, 2015, EN 747-1:2012 + A1: 2015 Bunk Beds and High Beds – Safety, Strength and Durability Requirements was published and will supersede the existing European standards by November 2015.

The major revisions in EN 747-1:2012+A1:2015 are as follows:
<ul>
	<li>The scope of the standard now applies to bunk beds with an upper surface of the top bed base of 600 mm or more and to high beds with a height to the upper surface of the bed base of 600 mm.</li>
	<li>A safety requirement for head entrapment has been added which applies only to openings where the lowest part is ≥ 600 mm from the floor.</li>
	<li>A requirement for the ventilation of the bed base has been defined as a minimum ventilation area of 35 cm² which can be fulfilled, for example, by 8 holes with a diameter of 24 mm each.</li>
	<li>Instructions for use, warnings and markings have been amended, with some new warnings and labelling in the form of text or pictogram now required.</li>
</ul>

<strong>New Low Voltage Directive 2014/35/EU</strong>

The New Legislative Framework (NLF), published in the Official Journal of the European Union in August 2008, is designed to help the internal market for goods perform better and to strengthen and modernise the conditions for placing a wide range of industrial products in the EU market. The Low Voltage Directive, one of the eight directives harmonised with NLF as a part of a so-called  ’Alignment Package’, will come into force on April 20, 2016.

The highlights of the New Low Voltage Directive 2014/35/EU are as follows:
<ul>
	<li>The manufacturers, the authorised representative, the importer and the distributor (i.e. economic operators) have the responsibility that products must be compliant with this Directive throughout the whole supply chain until the product gets to the end user.</li>
	<li>The traceability of economic operators throughout the whole supply chain must be unambiguous. The electrical equipment should indicate his name, registered trade name or registered trade mark and the postal address at which he can be contacted.</li>
	<li>The manufacturer has to compile the technical documentation, which must make it possible to assess the electrical equipment’s conformity to the relevant requirements. It must also include an adequate analysis and assessment of the risk. The manufacturer is responsible for the risk assessment and the implementation of the necessary measures.</li>
	<li>The Declaration of Conformity template, found in Annex IV, must contain the elements in Module A in Annex III, be continuously updated and be translated into the language or languages required by the Member State in which it is placed on the market.  The Declaration of Conformity must be completed by the economic operator and made available upon the request of the authorities.</li>
</ul>
